mpleting the initialization of the)A123 428 :M-.405(exception-declaration in the matching handler, calls a user function)A123 438 :M-.41(that exits via an uncaught exception,)A77 458 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 478 :M-.404(- when an exception handling mechanism, after completing evaluation of the)A123 488 :M-.404(object to be thrown but before either completing the initialization of the)A123 498 :M-.404(exception-declaration in the matching handler or entering unexpected\(\))A123 508 :M-.405(due to the throw, calls a user function that exits via an uncaught)A123 518 :M-.443(exception,)A77 538 :M-.408(Current wording in 18.6.3.3p2 for terminate\(\):)A113 558 :M-.405(Effects: Calls the terminate_handler function in effect immediately)A113 568 :M-.407(after evaluating the throw-expression \(18.6.3.1\).)A77 588 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 608 :M-.405(Effects: Calls the terminate_handler function in effect immediately)A113 618 :M-.407(after evaluating the throw-expression \(18.6.3.1\).)A113 628 :M-.406(Effects: If terminate\(\) is called by the implementation,)A113 638 :M-.405(uncaught_exception\(\) returns true when called at any point after)A113 648 :M-.419(entry to terminate\(\).)A77 668 :M-.407(Current wording in 18.6.4 for uncaught_exception\(\):)A113 688 :M-.405(Returns: true after completing evaluation of a throw-expression until)A113 698 :M-.404(completing initialization of the exception-declaration in the matching)Aendp%%Page: 2 2%%BeginPageSetupinitializepage(Bill Gibbons; page: 2 of 10)setjob%%EndPageSetupgS 0 0 552 730 rC41 29 468 677 rC113 38 :Mf0_9 sf-.406(handler \(15.5.3\). This includes stack unwinding \(15.2\).)A77 58 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 78 :M-.405(Returns: true after completing evaluation of a throw-expression until)A113 88 :M-.405(either completing initialization of the exception-declaration in the)A113 98 :M-.405(matching handler \(15.5.3\) or entering unexpected\(\) due to the throw;)A113 108 :M-.405(or after entering terminate\(\) for any reason other than an explicit)A113 118 :M-.405(call to terminate\(\). [Note: this includes stack unwinding \(15.2\).])A42 138 :M-.403(==========================================================================================)A42 158 :M-.408(2. Correct the semantics of "dynamic_cast".)A42 178 :M-.403(\(Rationale: it was the intent that access checking in dyanamic_cast mimic the checking)A42 188 :M-.403(which would be done by a single static cast \(for direct downcasts\) or a pair of static)A42 198 :M-.404(casts to the most derived type and then to the result type \(for cross-casts\).  The)A42 208 :M-.404(current wording does not do this, and also has an unintended bug allowing unsafe)A42 218 :M-.406(direct downcasts in some situations.  Core issue 549.\))A42 238 :M-.408(Move we amend the working paper as follows:)A77 258 :M-.414(Current wording in 5.2.7p8:)A113 278 :M-.405(The run-time check logically executes like this: If, in the most)A113 288 :M-.405(derived object pointed \(referred\) to by v, v points \(refers\) to a)A113 298 :M-.405(public base class sub-object of a T object, and if only one object)A113 308 :M-.405(of type T is derived from the sub-object pointed \(referred\) to by v,)A113 318 :M-.405(the result is a pointer \(an lvalue referring\) to that T object.)A113 328 :M-.405(Otherwise, if the type of the most derived object has an unambiguous)A113 338 :M-.405(public base class of type T, the result is a pointer \(reference\) to)A113 348 :M-.408(the T sub-object of the most derived object.)A77 368 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 388 :M-.407(The run-time check logically executes like this:)A113 408 :M-.405(- If, in the most derived object pointed \(referred\) to by v, v points)A113 418 :M-.405(\(refers\) to a public base class sub-object of a T object, and if only)A113 428 :M-.404(one object of type T is derived from the sub-object pointed \(referred\))A113 438 :M-.404(to by v, the result is a pointer \(an lvalue referring\) to that T object.)A113 458 :M-.404(- Otherwise, if v points \(refers\) to a public base class sub-object of)A113 468 :M-.405(the most derived object, and the type of the most derived object has)A113 478 :M-.404(an unambiguous base class of type T, the result is a pointer \(reference\))A113 488 :M-.407(to the T sub-object of the most derived object.)A77 508 :M-.413(Current wording in 5.2.7p10:)A113 528 :M-.412(class A { virtual void f\(\); };)A113 538 :M-.412(class B { virtual void g\(\); };)A113 548 :M-.409(class D : public virtual A, private B {};)A113 558 :M-.456(void g\(\))A113 568 :M({)S133 578 :M-.532(D d;)A133 588 :M-.407(B* bp = \(B*\)&d;  // cast needed to break protection)A133 598 :M-.406(A* ap = &d;      // public derivation, no cast needed)A133 608 :M-.408(D& dr = dynamic_cast<D&>\(*bp\);  // succeeds)A133 618 :M-.408(ap = dynamic_cast<A*>\(bp\);      // succeeds)A133 628 :M-.409(bp = dynamic_cast<B*>\(ap\);      // fails)A133 638 :M-.408(ap = dynamic_cast<A*>\(&dr\);     // succeeds)A133 648 :M-.409(bp = dynamic_cast<B*>\(&dr\);     // fails)A113 658 :M(})S77 678 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 698 :M-.412(class A { virtual void f\(\); };)Aendp%%Page: 3 3%%BeginPageSetupinitializepage(Bill Gibbons; page: 3 of 10)setjob%%EndPageSetupgS 0 0 552 730 rC41 29 468 677 rC113 38 :Mf0_9 sf-.412(class B { virtual void g\(\); };)A113 48 :M-.409(class D : public virtual A, private B {};)A113 58 :M-.456(void g\(\))A113 68 :M({)S133 78 :M-.532(D d;)A133 88 :M-.407(B* bp = \(B*\)&d;  // cast needed to break protection)A133 98 :M-.406(A* ap = &d;      // public derivation, no cast needed)A133 108 :M-.409(D& dr = dynamic_cast<D&>\(*bp\);  // fails)A133 118 :M-.409(ap = dynamic_cast<A*>\(bp\);      // fails)A133 128 :M-.409(bp = dynamic_cast<B*>\(ap\);      // fails)A133 138 :M-.408(ap = dynamic_cast<A*>\(&dr\);     // succeeds)A133 148 :M-.409(bp = dynamic_cast<B*>\(&dr\);     // fails)A113 158 :M(})S42 178 :M-.403(==========================================================================================)A42 198 :M-.403(3. Clarify the semantics of throwing an exception object of array or function type, as)A42 208 :M-.456(follows:)A42 228 :M-.404(\(Rationale: initializing the handler in an exception-declaration is intended to)A42 238 :M-.404(parallel initializing the parameter in a function call.  But the handler)A42 248 :M-.404(type is not known at the point of the throw, and there is no way to initialize)A42 258 :M-.404(the exception temporary if the thrown expression has array or function type.)A42 268 :M-.404(So the array-to-pointer and function-to-pointer conversions should be done at the)A42 278 :M-.404(throw and the corresponding adjustments should be made to the handler type.)A42 288 :M-.425(Core issue 678.\))A42 308 :M-.408(Move we amend the working paper as follows:)A77 328 :M-.415(Current wording in 15.1p3:)A113 348 :M-.405(A throw-expression initializes a temporary object of the static)A113 358 :M-.405(type of the operand of throw, ignoring the top-level cv-qualifiers)A113 368 :M-.405(of the operand\325s type, and uses that temporary to initialize the)A113 378 :M-.407(appropriately-typed variable named in the handler.)A77 398 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 418 :M-.405(A throw-expression initializes a temporary object, the type of which)A113 428 :M-.405(is determined by removing any top-level cv-qualifiers from the static)A113 438 :M-.405(type of the operand of throw and adjusting the type from \322array of T\323)A113 448 :M-.405(or \322function returning T\323 to \322pointer to T\323 or \322pointer to function)A113 458 :M-.405(returning T,\323 respectively. The temporary is used to initialize the)A113 468 :M-.407(appropriately-typed variable named in the handler.)A77 488 :M-.409(New paragraph between 15.3p1 and 15.3p2:)A113 508 :M-.405(A handler of type "array of T" or "function returning pointer to T")A113 518 :M-.405(is adjusted to be type "pointer to T" or "pointer to function)A113 528 :M-.414(returning T", respectively.)A42 548 :M-.403(==========================================================================================)A42 568 :M-.404(4. Clarify when class templates are instantiated during a "trial parse".)A42 588 :M-.404(\(Rationale: template-ids used as qualifiers must be instantiated to determine)A42 598 :M-.404(whether the qualified name is a type.  So the working paper note to the)A42 608 :M-.405(effect that instantiation is not done in a trial parse is incorrect.)A42 618 :M-.404(The proposed resolution makes any program for which it matters ill-formed.)A42 628 :M-.425(Core issue 671.\))A42 648 :M-.408(Move we amend the working paper as follows:)A77 668 :M-.415(Current wording in 6.8p3:)A113 688 :M-.405(The disambiguation is purely syntactic; that is, the meaning of)A113 698 :M-.405(the names occurring in such a statement, beyond whether they are)Aendp%%Page: 4 4%%BeginPageSetupinitializepage(Bill Gibbons; page: 4 of 10)setjob%%EndPageSetupgS 0 0 552 730 rC41 29 468 677 rC113 38 :Mf0_9 sf-.405(type-ids or not, is not used in or changed by the disambiguation.)A113 48 :M-.405(Disambiguation precedes parsing, and a statement disambiguated as)A113 58 :M-.405(a declaration may be an ill-formed declaration. [Note: because)A113 68 :M-.405(the disambiguation is purely syntactic, template instantiation)A113 78 :M-.406(does not take place during the disambiguation step. ])A77 98 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 118 :M-.405(The disambiguation is purely syntactic; that is, the meaning of)A113 128 :M-.405(the names occurring in such a statement, beyond whether they are)A113 138 :M-.405(type-ids or not, is not used in or changed by the disambiguation.)A113 148 :M-.406(Class templates appearing in qualifiers are instantiated as)A113 158 :M-.406(necessary to determine if the qualified name is a type-id.)A113 168 :M-.405(Disambiguation precedes parsing, and a statement disambiguated as)A113 178 :M-.405(a declaration may be an ill-formed declaration. If, during parsing,)A113 188 :M-.405(a name in a template parameter is bound differently than it would)A113 198 :M-.405(be bound during a trial parse, the program is ill-formed.  No)A113 208 :M-.405(diagnostic is required. [Note: this can occur only when the name)A113 218 :M-.409(is declared earlier in the declaration. ])A42 238 :M-.403(==========================================================================================)A42 258 :M-.404(5. Editorial change to restore intended interaction of default arguments and using-)A42 268 :M-.432(declarations.)A42 288 :M-.404(\(Rationale: the working paper was changed in a way not intended by a motion about)A42 298 :M-.406(default arguments.  The original intent is restored.\))A77 318 :M-.415(Current wording n 8.3.6p9:)A113 338 :M-.405(When a declaration of a function is introduced by way of a using)A113 348 :M-.405(declaration \(7.3.3\), any default argument information associated with)A113 358 :M-.405(the declaration is imported as well. If the function is redeclared)A113 368 :M-.405(thereafter in the namespace with additional default arguments, the)A113 378 :M-.41(imported declaration is not affected.)A77 398 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 418 :M-.405(When a declaration of a function is introduced by way of a using)A113 428 :M-.405(declaration \(7.3.3\), any default argument information associated with)A113 438 :M-.405(the declaration is made known as well. If the function is redeclared)A113 448 :M-.405(thereafter in the namespace with additional default arguments, the)A113 458 :M-.404(additional arguments are also made known through the using declaration.)A42 478 :M-.403(==========================================================================================)A42 498 :M-.404(6. Clarify when overload resolution causes class template instantiation.)A42 518 :M-.404(\(Rationale: the working paper implies that every possible conversion of an argument)A42 528 :M-.404(to a potential parameter must be considered.  This can result in a massive number)A42 538 :M-.404(of class template instantiations, most of which can usually be avoided by a)A42 548 :M-.404(careful implementation of the overload resolution algorithm \(because a function is)A42 558 :M-.404(known to be nonviable or not the best match through information about other)A42 568 :M-.413(parameters.  Core issue 676.\))A42 588 :M-.408(Move we amend the working paper as follows:)A77 608 :M-.404(Remove the editorial box #14 in 14.7.1p3, and add a new paragraph in its)A77 618 :M-.478(place:)A113 638 :M-.404(If the overload resolution process can determine the correct function to)A113 648 :M-.404(call without instantiating a class template definition, it is unspecified )A113 658 :M-.406(whether that instantiation actually takes place.  [Example:)A149 678 :M-.413(template <class T> struct S {)A185 688 :M-.427(operator int\(\);)A149 698 :M-.797(};)Aendp%%Page: 5 5%%BeginPageSetupinitializepage(Bill Gibbons; page: 5 of 10)setjob%%EndPageSetupgS 0 0 552 730 rC41 29 468 677 rC149 48 :Mf0_9 sf-.435(void f\(int\);)A149 58 :M-.425(void f\(S<int>&\);)A149 68 :M-.406(void f\(S<float>\); // instantiation of S<float> allowed)A231 78 :M-.421(// but not required)A149 98 :M-.42(void g\(S<int>& sr\) {)A185 108 :M-.478(f\(sr\);)A231 108 :M-.411(// instantiation of S<int> allowed)A231 118 :M-.421(// but not required)A149 128 :M-.797(};)A113 148 :M-.429(- end example])A42 168 :M-.403(==========================================================================================)A42 178 :M(.)S42 188 :M-.404(7. Clarify the set of associated names used for argument-dependent name lookup.)A42 208 :M-.404(\(Rationale: the working paper does not address how any non-type arguments and)A42 218 :M-.404(template template arguments in a template-id affect the set of associated names.)A42 228 :M-.415(Core issues 686 and 703.\))A42 248 :M-.408(Move we amend the working paper as follows:)A77 268 :M-.405(Add the following footnote to 3.4.2p2, after "\311 be considered;":)A113 288 :M-.405(The set of namespaces is determined entirely by the types of the)A113 298 :M-.406(arguments.  Typedef names used to specify the types do not)A113 308 :M-.417(contribute to this set.)A77 328 :M-.414(Current wording in 3.4.2p2:)A113 348 :M-.406(\321 If T is a template-id, its associated namespaces are the)A123 358 :M-.405(namespace of the template and the namespaces associated with)A123 368 :M-.412(the type of template arguments.)A77 388 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 408 :M-.406(- If T is a template-id, its associated namespaces are the)A123 418 :M-.406(namespaces of the template, the namespaces associated with)A123 428 :M-.406(the types of the template arguments provided for template)A123 438 :M-.405(type parameters \(excluding template template parameters\), and)A123 448 :M-.407(the namespaces of any template template arguments.)A42 468 :M-.403(==========================================================================================)A42 488 :M-.404(8. Editorial change to clarify a description of exception type matching.)A42 508 :M-.404(\(Rationale: there were two ways to interpret the text.  It was clear to)A42 518 :M-.411(Core-III which one was intended.\))A77 538 :M-.415(Current wording in 15.3/2:)A113 558 :M-.404(A handler is a match for a throw-expression with an object of type E if)A113 568 :M-.598(...)A113 578 :M-.404(\321 the handler is of type cv1 T* cv2 and E is a pointer type that can be)A123 588 :M-.405(converted to the type of the handler by a standard pointer conversion)A123 598 :M-.404(\(4.10\) not involving conversions to pointers to private or protected or)A123 608 :M-.405(ambiguous classes, or a qualification-conversion \(4.4\), or a)A123 618 :M-.415(combination of these two.)A77 638 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 658 :M-.404(A handler is a match for a throw-expression with an object of type E if)A113 668 :M-.598(...)A113 678 :M-.404(\321 the handler is of type cv1 T* cv2 and E is a pointer type that can be)A123 688 :M-.406(converted to the type of the handler by a combination of)Aendp%%Page: 6 6%%BeginPageSetupinitializepage(Bill Gibbons; page: 6 of 10)setjob%%EndPageSetupgS 0 0 552 730 rC41 29 468 677 rC149 38 :Mf0_9 sf-.405(- a standard pointer conversion \(4.10\) not involving conversions)A149 48 :M-.406(to pointers to private or protected or ambiguous classes)A149 68 :M-.413(- a qualification conversion)A42 88 :M-.403(==========================================================================================)A42 108 :M-.404(9. Clarify that member templates do not suppress implicit copy/assign functions.)A42 128 :M-.403(\(Rationale: The automatic declaration of implicit copy constructors and copy assignment)A42 138 :M-.403(operators should not be affected by the possibility of a member template specialization)A42 148 :M-.403(meeting the requirements for a copy constructor or copy assignment operator.  Issue 8.3)A42 158 :M-.422(in 96-0158/N0976.\))A42 178 :M-.408(Move we amend the working paper as follows:)A77 198 :M-.415(Current wording in 12.8p2:)A113 218 :M-.404(A constructor for class X is a copy constructor if its first parameter)A113 228 :M-.405(is of type X&, const X&, volatile X& or const volatile X&, and either)A113 238 :M-.404(there are no other parameters or else all other parameters have default)A113 248 :M-.422(arguments \(8.3.6\).)A77 268 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 288 :M-.404(A non-template constructor for class X is a copy constructor if its first)A113 298 :M-.404(parameter is of type X&, const X&, volatile X& or const volatile X&, and)A113 308 :M-.404(either there are no other parameters or else all other parameters have)A113 318 :M-.404(default arguments \(8.3.6\).  [Footnote: Because a template constructor is)A113 328 :M-.405(never a copy constructor, the presence of such a template does not)A113 338 :M-.405(suppress the implicit declaration of a copy constructor.  Template)A113 348 :M-.404(constructors participate in overload resolution with other constructors,)A113 358 :M-.404(including copy constructors, and a template constructor may be used to copy)A113 368 :M-.405(an object if it provides a better match than other constructors. ])A77 388 :M-.415(Current wording in 12.8p9:)A113 408 :M-.405(A user-declared copy assignment operator X::operator= is a non-static)A113 418 :M-.405(member function of class X with exactly one parameter of type X, X&,)A113 428 :M-.408(const X&, volatile X& or const volatile X&.)A77 448 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 468 :M-.405(A user-declared copy assignment operator X::operator= is a non-static)A113 478 :M-.405(non-template member function of class X with exactly one parameter of)A113 488 :M-.405(type X, X&, const X&, volatile X& or const volatile X&.  [Footnote:)A113 498 :M-.405(Because a template assignment operator is never a copy assignment)A113 508 :M-.404(operator, the presence of such a template does not suppress the implicit)A113 518 :M-.404(declaration of a copy assignment operator.  Template assignment operators)A113 528 :M-.405(participate in overload resolution with other assignment operators,)A113 538 :M-.404(including copy assignment operators, and a template assignment operator)A113 548 :M-.404(may be used to copy an object if it provides a better match than other)A113 558 :M-.417(assignment operators. ])A42 578 :M-.403(==========================================================================================)A42 598 :M-.404(10. Assume a dependent qualified name is a type in some additional contexts.)A42 618 :M-.403(\(Rationale: There are to two contexts where a qualified name is assumed to be a type,)A42 628 :M-.403(and the typename keyword is neither necessary nor permitted to be applied to the name.)A42 638 :M-.404(The two contexts are qualifiers \(e.g. B in A::B::C\) and elaborated names)A42 648 :M-.403(\(e.g. B in struct A::B\).  But there are also two contexts where a qualified name must)A42 658 :M-.403(be a type name, and the typename keyword is not permitted, yet the name is not assumed)A42 668 :M-.403(to be a type name.  \(That is, typename is both required and forbidden.\)  These contexts)A42 678 :M-.403(are base class specifiers and member/base initializers.  These two cases should be made)A42 688 :M-.404(to behave like the first two, i.e. typename is assumed.  Core issue 736.\))Aendp%%Page: 7 7%%BeginPageSetupinitializepage(Bill Gibbons; page: 7 of 10)setjob%%EndPageSetupgS 0 0 552 730 rC41 29 468 677 rC42 38 :Mf0_9 sf-.408(Move we amend the working paper as follows:)A77 58 :M-.408(Add a new paragraph between 14.6p3 ad 14.6p4:)A113 78 :M-.405(The keyword typename is not permitted in a base-specifier or in a)A113 88 :M-.404(mem-initializer.  In these contexts a qualified-name that depends on a)A113 98 :M-.406(template parameter is implicitly assumed to be a type name.)A42 118 :M-.403(==========================================================================================)A42 138 :M-.404(11. Editorial change to clarify that \322friend class T\323 is not permitted.)A42 158 :M-.405(\(Rationale: This is a frequently asked question.  Core issue 738.\))A77 178 :M-.413(Current wording in 7.1.5.3p5:)A113 198 :M-.404(If the identifier resolves to a typedef-name or a template type-parameter,)A113 208 :M-.408(the elaborated-type-specifier is ill-formed.)A77 228 :M-.425(Revised wording:)A113 248 :M-.404(If the identifier resolves to a typedef-name or a template type-parameter,)A113 258 :M-.404(the elab